lUuNhVA | title=Myeik Sea View Condo Phase 1 Launched | publisher=Eleven Broadcasting | date=2018-01-11 | language=Burmese | accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=cqhp-sv>{{cite web | url=https://www.cqhp.org/project/sea-view-condominium/ | title=Sea View Condominium | accessdate=2020-04-16 | publisher=CQHP Myanmar}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sea View Condominium|Sea View Condominium IV]]\n|-\n| [[The Central, Yangon|The Central]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ?\n| 27\n| 2020\n| Kaba Aye Pagoda Road\n| <ref name=mt-20200211>{{cite journal | author=Yi-Ywe Myint | url=https://www.mmtimes.com/news/metros-top-picks-yangon-housing-projects.html | title=Metro\u2019s top picks of Yangon housing projects | work=The Myanmar Times | date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[68 Residence]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ''{{convert|93|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}''\n| 26\n| 2020\n| At Saya San and Kaba Aye Pagoda Roads\n| <ref name=mt-20200211/>\n|-\n| [[Peninsula Residences]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ''{{convert|93|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}''\n| 26\n| \n| \n| <ref name=mt-2018-peninsula>{{cite journal | author=Yi-Ywe Myint | url=https://www.mmtimes.com/news/sales-peninsula-residences-yangon-commence-month.html | title=Sales at Peninsula Residences Yangon to commence this month | work=The Myanmar Times | date=2018-03-27}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Landmark Towers|Landmark Towers III]]\n| \n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Yangon]]\n| ''{{convert|93|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}''\n| 26\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2021\n| \n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref name=emporis-ygn-2/>\n|-\n| [[Landmark Towers|Landmark Towers IV]]\n| \n| ''{{convert|90|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}''\n| 25\n| \n|-\n| [[Kanbe Towers|Kanbe Towers I]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | \n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Yangon]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | ''{{convert|90|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 25\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2020\n| rowspan=\"4\" | \n| rowspan=\"4\" | <ref name=emporis-ygn-2/>\n|-\n| [[Kanbe Towers|Kanbe Towers II]]\n|-\n| [[Kanbe Towers|Kanbe Towers III]]\n|-\n| [[Kanbe Towers|Kanbe Towers IV]]\n|}\n\n==Timeline of tallest buildings==\nBecause many of the exact building heights are not known, the timeline below may be incomplete. The estimated heights are given in ''italics''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe6\"\n! Name\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n! Location\n! Height: <br/>m (ft)\n! Floors\n! Years as tallest\n! Notes\n! References\n|-\n| [[Asia Plaza Hotel]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| {{convert|58.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 17\n| 1988\u20131996\n| \n| <ref name=sp-aph>{{cite web | url=https://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=27157 | title=Asia Plaza Hotel | publisher=Skyscraper Page | accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sule Shangri-La Hotel]]\n| [[File:Central Business District 05.jpg|alt=|center|frameless|100px]]\n| [[Yangon]]\n| {{convert|80.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 22\n| 1996\u20131999\n| Formerly, Traders Hotel\n| <ref name=sp-traders>{{cite web | url=https://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=40734 | title=Traders Hotel | publisher=Skyscraper Page | accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sakura Tower]]\n| [[File:Sakura Tower, Yangon, Myanmar.jpg|alt=|center|frameless|100px]]\n| [[Yangon]]\n| {{convert|100|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 20\n| 1999\u20132016\n| \n| <ref group=note>According to the tower's web site, {{cite web | url=http://www.sakura-tower-yangon.com/ | title=About Sakura Tower | date=2020-04-16}}, it is a 100-meter high 20-story tower, completed in 1999. <br/> A 2014 National Geographic article, {{cite journal | url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/11/141112-myanmar-burma-yangon-rangoon-heritage-architecture/ | title=The Race to Save Architecture in Myanmar's Biggest City | journal=The National Geographic | date=2014-11-13}}, identifies the Sakura Tower as the tallest building in Yangon.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sedona Hotel II]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ''{{convert|104|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}''\n| 29\n| 2016\u20132018\n| \n| <ref name=emporis/>\n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City I]] \n| \n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Yangon]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | {{convert|109.7|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 33\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2018\u20132019\n| rowspan=\"4\" | \n| rowspan=\"4\" | <ref name=dp-gc/>\n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City II]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City III]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City IV]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Diamond Inya Palace]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ''{{convert|122|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}''\n| 34\n| 2019\u2013present\n| \n| <ref name=emporis/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest structures in Myanmar]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Yangon]]\n\n==External sources==\n* [https://www.cqhp.org/ Committee for Quality Control of High Rise Building Construction Projects, Republic of the Union of Myanmar]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{TBSW}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tallest Buildings in Myanmar, List Of}}\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Lists of tallest buildings in Asia|Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Lists of tallest structures by country|Myanmar]]\n", "text_old": "This is a '''list of tallest buildings''' in [[Myanmar]]. The list includes habitable buildings standing at or above 90 meters (295 feet) but excludes other structures above 90 meters such as the [[Laykyun Sekkya|Laykyun Sekkya Buddha Statue]], the [[Shwemawdaw Pagoda]], the [[Shwesandaw Pagoda (Bagan)|Shwesandaw Pagoda]], or the [[Shwedagon Pagoda]]. For other tallest structures, see [[List of tallest structures in Myanmar]].\n\nAll of Myanmar's tallest buildings are [[High-rise building|high rises]]. The country does not have a [[skyscraper]]\u2014i.e. one at least 150 meters tall as defined by the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] and [[Emporis]].<ref name=skyscraper>{{cite web | url=https://theurbandeveloper.com/articles/which-world-city-has-the-most-skyscrapers | title=Which World City Has The Most Skyscrapers?\" | publisher=The Urban Developer | date=2016-03-11 | accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=emporis-myanmar>{{cite web | url=https://www.emporis.com/country/100112/myanmar | title=Myanmar | publisher=Emporis | accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Most of the tallest buildings are located in [[Yangon]] where zoning regulations restrict the maximum height of buildings to 127 meters (417 feet) above sea level,<ref name=yangon-height>{{cite web | last=Lau | first=Bo Yee | url=https://fac.arch.hku.hk/asian-cities-research/yangon-2007-2017-height-restriction-policies-that-shape-both-the-urban-and-economic-landscape/ | title=Yangon (2007-2017): Height Restriction Policies That Shape Both the Urban and Economic Landscape | publisher=The University of Hong Kong}}</ref><ref name=lincoln>{{cite web | url=https://www.lincolnmyanmar.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/4-August-2016-Seminar-land-law-stamp-duty.pdf | author=Lincoln Legal Services Myanmar | title=LAND LAW / STAMP DUTY IN MYANMAR | date=August 2016 | accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref> in order to prevent buildings from overtaking the [[Shwedagon Pagoda]].<ref name=obg>{{cite web | author=Oxford Business Group| title=Striking a balance: New housing and office projects are changing the landscape of cities | url=https://oxfordbusinessgroup.com/overview/striking-balance-new-housing-and-office-projects-are-changing-landscape-cities | accessdate=2020-04-18 | year=2013}}</ref> The first ever attempt to build a skyscraper in the country\u2014a 195-meter (640-foot) tower in [[downtown Yangon]]\u2014<ref name=555-Merchant>{{cite web | url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1210437/555-merchant-office-tower-yangon-myanmar | title=555 Merchant Office Tower | publisher=Emporis | accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref> faced intense opposition by local conservationists, and was cancelled in 2014.<ref name=nat-geo>{{cite journal | last=Palmer | first=Alex | url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/11/141112-myanmar-burma-yangon-rangoon-heritage-architecture/ | title=The Race to Save Architecture in Myanmar's Biggest City | journal=The National Geographic | date=2014-11-13}}</ref>\n\n==Tallest buildings==\nThe following list ranks completed buildings in Myanmar that stand ''about'' 90 meters (295 feet) or taller based on the estimates by Emporis, unless otherwise stated. Because of its use of Emporis's estimates, the list may not be fully accurate\u2014in terms of inclusion and rankings. (Emporis estimates the height of buildings based on the number of floors; as a result, buildings with the same number of floors are estimated at the same height.<ref group=note>See Emporis's estimates for Yangon buildings here: [https://www.emporis.com/city/101677/yangon-myanmar/status/all-buildings].</ref>) The estimated heights are preceded with a \"~\".\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable zebra\"\n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe6\"\n! Rank\n! Name\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Image\n! Location\n! Height: <br/>m (ft)\n! Floors\n! Year\n! Notes\n! References\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Diamond Inya Palace]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ~{{convert|122|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 34\n| 2019\n| \n| <ref name=emporis>{{cite web | url=https://www.emporis.com/statistics/tallest-buildings/country/100112/myanmar | title=Myanmar's tallest buildings - Top 20 | publisher=EMPORIS | accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City I]] \n| \n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Yangon]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | {{convert|109.7|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 33\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"4\" | \n| rowspan=\"4\" | <ref name=dp-gc>{{cite web | url=https://www.dotproperty.com.mm/en/condo/6259/golden-city | title=Golden City | publisher=Dot Property | accessdate=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City II]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City III]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Golden City, Yangon|Golden City IV]]\n| \n|-\n| 6\n| [[Lotte Hotel Yangon Residences]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ~{{convert|104|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 29\n| 2017\n| \n| <ref name=emporis/>\n|-\n| 6=\n| [[Sedona Hotel II]]\n| \n| [[Yangon]]\n| ~{{convert|104|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| 29\n